'''Francis Michael Gambacorta''' (8 July 1913 - 1 December 2000) was a [[US Navy]] Captain. He graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis, Class of 1935 and served onboard [[submarines]] in [[World War II]], receiving the [[Silver Star]] award for actions in Japan in 1942.<ref name="militarytimes">{{cite web|title=Valor awards for Francis Michael Gambacorta|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=55642|website=valor.militarytimes.com|accessdate=13 May 2016}}</ref>
Later, Gambacorta served as captain of the USS Wyandot that transported the party which established [[Ellsworth Station]], an [[Antarctica|Antarctic]] research station, at the outset of the International Geophysical Year. Unloading at the station site on the Filchner Ice Shelf began in January 1957.<ref name="deepfreeze">{{cite book|last1=Belanger|first1=Dian Olson|title=Deep freeze : the United States, the international geophysical year, and the origins of Antarctica's age of science.|date=2010|publisher=Univ Pr Of Colorado|location=Niwot|isbn=1607320665}}<!--|accessdate=13 May 2016--></ref> [[Gambacorta Peak]], a mountain near the Station, was named for him by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN).<ref name="usgs">{{cite web|title=Antarctica Detail: Gambacorta Peak|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/apex/f?p=gnispq:5:0::NO::P5_ANTAR_ID:5448|website=geonames.usgs.gov|publisher=US Geological Survey|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>
